<%= chapter_block extra_class: "mt-5" do %>
  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Choke points</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    The most obvious use for a wall is to close off a choke point. Wait for an enemy to enter, place a wall behind him, and finish him without having to worry about the rest of the enemy team. In the "<%= link_to "Map specific", "#" %>" chapter I will be going over specific choke points and how to utilize them.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Separating teams</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    You don't always have a choke point to support your walls. In the middle of a team fight a wall can be a great way of separating enemies away from their healers, dps, or whatever it might be. You can place your wall in the middle of an open field, and still win a few seconds, which might be enough to get a kill or two. Inside buildings it can be extra effective, as there might not be a way around your wall.
  </p>

  <p>
    After losing a fight on 2CP maps enemy teams tend to over extend. Use this to your advantage and catch those who do.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Forcing a direction</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    Even if your wall does not block off anything, it can still force an enemy to walk a particular direction. This allows your team to easily fire at the enemy, as their movement will be very predictable.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Mobility</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    Wall below your feet to lift yourself up. Wall below your teammates feet to lift them up. You can help yourself and your team reach places your enemy might not expect. In the "<%= link_to "Map specific", "#" %>" chapter I will be going over specific spots. But in general, reach places to get away from enemies or surprise them. Lift yourself over a wall, and flank them. Mei doesn't have great mobility, but she can reach unexpected places, this is especially useful when trying to land a good ultimate. Mei is the only hero that can create mobility for her teammates (and enemies).
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Bridging gaps</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    There's many gaps that mobile characters can use to get to an objective faster. Those without mobility often have to take the long route, but with your help you can get them over.
  </p>

  <p>
    When trying to find proper spots for you and your team to reach, look for objects that might help you get higher up. Think of benches, rocks, anything that might give you that little bit of extra reach. The payload's position might open up paths that were unreachable.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Creating high ground</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    High ground is incredibly important. It allows you to easily land headshots on your opponent while making it more difficult for them. Lifting yourself up in the middle of a duel can give you a large advantage.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Saving yourself and your team</h4>

  <p class="mt-0 mb-2">
    Blocking ultimates, stopping Roadhog hooks, it will all win you favor with your teammates. You can play Mei as more of a tank oriented role by focussing on keeping your teammates safe. Lifting your supports away from flankers can give them enough time to heal up and make a safe escape. Try to track the abilities your enemies use, predict ultimates and be ready to block them. Practically any ability can be block, but be careful to not block those of your teammates.
  </p>

  <label class="content-toggle">
    Toggle image

    <input type="checkbox" class="content-toggle__input">
    <div class="content-toggle__inner">
      <p class="mt-0 mb-3">
        My team gets caught in a Zarya ultimate, with a D.va ultimate coming their way. A well timed wall saved them from certain death.
      </p>

      <div class="relative" style="padding-bottom: 54%">
        <iframe src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/AccomplishedExhaustedChanticleer" class="absolute pin-t pin-l" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" width="100%" height="100%" allowfullscreen></iframe>
      </div>
    </div>
  </label>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Closing escape points</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    If you know your team will enter a room filled with enemies, you can often pre-emptively close an escape point from outside of that room. This will force the enemy to stay in the room and out of potential cover. This can of course also work on smaller scale, when you see a single enemy in a room.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Stalling</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    Whether it's Payload or Point control, Mei's wall in combination with Cryo-freeze allows her to keep contesting a point for a long time. Try lifting yourself up, many enemy expect you to be behind the wall, and not on top. This in turn opens up opportunities to pick off enemies, while you wait for the rest of your team to arrive.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Blocking healthpacks</h4>

  <p class="mt-0 mb-2">
    Ice Wall is thick enough to block healthpacks when placed right on top of them. Of course those going for healthpacks are often low health, and have used their mobility to try and get there, allowing you to pick up and easy kill.
  </p>

  <label class="content-toggle">
    Toggle image

    <input type="checkbox" class="content-toggle__input">
    <div class="content-toggle__inner">
      <p class="mt-0 mb-3">
        <iframe src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/ThoughtfulDeficientLeveret" class="absolute pin-t pin-l" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" width="100%" height="100%" allowfullscreen></iframe>
      </p>

      <div class="relative" style="padding-bottom: 54%">

      </div>
    </div>
  </label>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Keeping enemies off of the objective</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    When overtime starts ticking fast, a well timed wall can be all that's needed to win the point. Closing up a choke point can easily win you the objective. Even when there is no choke point, the extra second it takes for enemies to walk around the wall can be all you need.
  </p>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">Bringing enemies in to view</h4>

  <p class="mt-0 mb-2">
    Enemies hiding behind a wall or a shield? Lift them up and bring them in to view! This can be especially useful when up against a Bastion who sits on the payload hiding behind a shield. Lift him up, and allow your team to hit him.
  </p>

  <label class="content-toggle">
    Toggle image

    <input type="checkbox" class="content-toggle__input">
    <div class="content-toggle__inner">
      <p class="mt-0 mb-3">
        In this clip you can see me lift Orisa away from her shield, allowing us to finish her.
      </p>

      <div class="relative" style="padding-bottom: 54%">
        <iframe src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/RequiredSecretAdouri" class="absolute pin-t pin-l" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" width="100%" height="100%" allowfullscreen></iframe>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-4 mb-3">
        An easy way to stop a protected Bastion on a payload is to simply lift him away from his shields.
      </p>

      <div class="relative" style="padding-bottom: 54%">
        <iframe src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/SpeedyGranularInganue" class="absolute pin-t pin-l" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" width="100%" height="100%" allowfullscreen></iframe>
      </div>
    </div>
  </label>

  <h4 class="mt-4 mb-2">General advise on using your Ice Wall</h4>

  <p class="mt-0">
    While the wall can be very benefitial, it can also hurt your team. As a general rule I make sure to take down my wall as soon as I now longer know exactly what it is stopping. If it is serving no purpose, it is better to drop it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Communication is key. Tell your team when you have caught someone and make sure to listen to calls when they are about to use their ultimate. The last thing you want to do is block a friendly would-be 6 man Reinhardt Shatter.
  </p>

  <p>
    Enemies can hear the sound of you starting to place your Ice Wall. As soon as you press you Ice Wall they here the same sound you do. Keep this in mind when trying to be sneaky.
  </p>

  <p>
    Too often I see a Mei only use her wall in choke points. An Ice Wall in the middle of an open field can still separate a tank for a few seconds, which is all you need.
  </p>

  <p class="mt-5 font-italic">
    Even with all these different subjects, we have only scratched the surface. In the map and hero specific chapters I will go over more specific uses for your wall. And even then, a lot of it comes down to your creativity and experience. There is no ability in the game that has such a vast amount of different uses.
  </p>
<% end %>

<%= chapter_block extra_class: "mt-5" do %>
  <h2 class="mt-0 mb-3" id="blizzard">Blizzard</h2>

  <p>
    Mei's ultimate is often used wrong. It's not supposed to get you those large multi kills. It's easy to get out of by most of the heroes, it doesn't deal a lot of damage, and it's difficult to properly hit multiple targets. What it is great at is area denial. You create this enormous area that the enemy would rather stay away from. This can be great to deny choke points, split enemy teams, and catch people out of position. In a lot of ways it serves a similar role to your wall, except with a deadly twist.
  </p>

  <p>
    Let's go over some important points.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>After landing it takes 1.5 seconds for the ultimate to activate.</li>
    <li>Targets are frozen after 1.5 seconds. This can be decreased by additionally hitted the enemy with your Endothermic Blaster.</li>
    <li>Blizzard lasts 5 seconds. Enemies are frozen as long as they are within the radius. The targets are no longer stunned after 1.5 seconds of leaving the radius, or the ability ending.</li>
    <li>Blizzard requires line of sight from the center of the ability.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    After throwing your ultimate, when it lands it takes 1.5 seconds for it to activate it's effect. This means that when throwing your ultimate from a distance, it can take a very long time to actually do anything. Thus giving your enemies a ton of time to prepare and react. For this reason, and many others, it's often a good idea to throw your ultimate directly at your feet. Other reasons include; Making sure you are in range to follow up on it properly, and making sure your ultimate does not get reflected or Defense Matrixed.<br>
    <em>Unfortunately due to buggy detection, it can take more than 1.5 seconds for it to activate. It can get stuck on some object and you will have to wait for it to reposition itself. This can sometimes take several seconds. Because of this I often make sure to throw it on a flat surface to make sure it activates right away.</em>
  </p>

  <p>
    Many heroes have one or more abilities that allow them to get out of your ultimate. This makes it very difficult to catch someone. When using your ultimate it can be a good idea to look for a spot with not many exits. Especially when closing one of those exits with your Ice Wall. This will of course not always be ideal. Sometimes you will have to use your ultimate in a big open space. This can be for a number of reasons; Forcing people away from an objective, splitting enemy teams, and trying to kill a single target. In all of these situations it can be a good idea to force on one specific enemy, to make sure you atleast get a kill. But even if you don't, the area control it gives can easily win you the fight. It forces enemies to use their movement abilities, which can make them vulnerable. This is similar to what a D.va Self-destruct is often used for.
  </p>
<% end %>

